# 5) Plot helper
plot_svm <- function(grid, title) {
  ggplot() +
    geom_contour_filled(data = grid, aes(x = x1, y = x2, z = decision),
                        breaks = c(-Inf, 0, Inf),
                        show.legend = FALSE, alpha = 0.6) +
    scale_fill_manual(values = c("#7fcdbb", "#fdcc8a")) +
    geom_contour(data = grid, aes(x = x1, y = x2, z = decision),
                 breaks = 0, color = "black", linewidth = 0.6) +
    geom_point(data = dat, aes(x = x1, y = x2, color = y),
               size = 1.2, alpha = 0.9) +
    scale_color_manual(values = c(A = "#1b9e77", B = "#7570b3")) +
    coord_equal(xlim = xlim, ylim = ylim, expand = TRUE) +
    labs(title = title, x = "variable 1", y = "variable 2") +
    theme_minimal(base_size = 11) +
    theme(legend.position = "none",
          plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", hjust = 0.5))
}

# 2) Helper to compute decision surface for an SVM model
decision_grid <- function(model, xlim, ylim, by = 0.02) {
  xs <- seq(xlim[1], xlim[2], by = by)
  ys <- seq(ylim[1], ylim[2], by = by)
  grid <- expand.grid(x1 = xs, x2 = ys)
  pred <- predict(model, grid, decision.values = TRUE, probability = FALSE)
  dv <- attr(pred, "decision.values")
  grid$decision <- as.numeric(dv)
  grid
}

# 4. Radial Basis (RBF) Kernel Data - inner cluster surrounded by outer points
n <- 1000
# Inner cluster (purple)
inner_x1 <- rnorm(n, 0, 0.3)
inner_x2 <- rnorm(n, 0, 0.3)

# Outer points (turquoise) - surrounding the inner cluster
theta_outer <- seq(0, 2*pi, length.out = n*2)
outer_x1 <- c(1.5*cos(theta_outer) + rnorm(n*2, 0, 0.2),
              runif(20, -2, 2))
outer_x2 <- c(1.5*sin(theta_outer) + rnorm(n*2, 0, 0.2),
              c(runif(10, 1.5, 2), runif(10, -2, -1.5)))

X_rbf <- cbind(
  x1 = c(inner_x1, outer_x1),
  x2 = c(inner_x2, outer_x2)
)
y_rbf <- factor(c(rep("B", n), rep("A", length(outer_x1))))
dat <- data.frame(x1 = X_rbf[,1], x2 = X_rbf[,2], y = y_rbf)

# 5. Sigmoid Kernel Data - three regions (blue-grey-blue pattern)
n <- 1000
# Generate random points
x1_vals <- runif(n*3, -2, 2)
x2_vals <- runif(n*3, -2, 2)

X_sigmoid <- cbind(x1 = x1_vals, x2 = x2_vals)

# Create three classes based on diagonal bands
y_sigmoid <- rep("B", n*3)  # Default to grey
diagonal_sum <- X_sigmoid[,1] + X_sigmoid[,2]
y_sigmoid[diagonal_sum < -1] <- "A"  # Lower-left region
y_sigmoid[diagonal_sum > 1] <- "A"   # Upper-right region
y_sigmoid <- factor(y_sigmoid)

dat <- data.frame(x1 = X_sigmoid[,1], x2 = X_sigmoid[,2], y = y_sigmoid)

# Fit SVM with sigmoid kernel - adjusted parameters for diagonal band pattern
svm_sig <- e1071::svm(y ~ ., 
                       data = dat, 
                       kernel = "sigmoid", 
                       gamma = 1,      # Increased for sharper transitions
                       coef0 = 1,   # Negative to help with the diagonal pattern
                       cost = 2,      # Higher cost for better boundary adherence
                       scale = FALSE, 
                       decision.values = TRUE)

# 4) Build decision grids
xlim <- range(dat$x1) + c(-0.5, 0.5)
ylim <- range(dat$x2) + c(-0.5, 0.5)

# Systematic parameter search
library(e1071)

# Define parameter grid once
param_ranges <- list(
  gamma = c(0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 0.5, 1, 2),
  coef0 = c(-2, -1, -0.5, 0, 0.5),
  cost = c(1, 10, 50, 100)
)

# Tune the model using the defined ranges
tuned_svm <- tune(svm, y ~ ., data = dat, 
                  kernel = "sigmoid",
                  ranges = param_ranges,
                  scale = TRUE)

# Get best model
svm_sig <- tuned_svm$best.model
print(tuned_svm$best.parameters)

# Check performance
table(Predicted = predict(svm_sig), Actual = dat$y)
